from collections import deque
def bfs(adj, start):
    seen={start}; q=deque([start]); order=[]
    while q:
        u=q.popleft(); order.append(u)
        for v in adj[u]:
            if v not in seen: seen.add(v); q.append(v)
    return order
g={0:[1,2],1:[0,3],2:[0,3],3:[1,2,4],4:[3]}
print(bfs(g, 0))   # 0,1,2,3,4 — level by level
```

BFS explores in rings of increasing distance, so it finds shortest paths in unweighted graphs and naturally orders nodes by hops from the source — the traversal behind reachability, shortest-path, and the neighborhood aggregation in graph neural networks.
